{"title_page": "Liepert", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n'''Liepert''' is a [[German language]] surname. It is similar to the surname [[Lippert]].\n\n== List of people with the surname ==\n\n* [[Beate G. Liepert]], Canadian scientist\n* [[Ron Liepert]] (born 1949), Canadian politician from [[Alberta]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Lippert]]\n*[[Limpertsberg]]\n* [[Liebertwolkwitz]]\n* [[Liedertswil]]\n* [[Liebert (company)]]\n{{Surname|}}\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Surnames of German origin]]\n[[Category:German-language surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n'''Liepert''' is a [[German language]] surname.It is similar to the surname [[Lippert]].\n\n== List of people with the surname ==\n\n* [[Beate G. Liepert]], Canadian scientist\n* [[Ron Liepert]] (born 1949), Canadian politician from [[Alberta]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Lippert]]\n*[[Limpertsberg]]\n* [[Liebertwolkwitz]]\n* [[Liedertswil]]\n* [[Liebert (company)]]\n{{Surname|}}\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Surnames of German origin]]\n[[Category:German-language surnames]]\n", "name_user": "MoonlightTulsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liepert"}
{"title_page": "Arnold Manoff", "text_new": "{{short description|American screenwriter and political activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Arnold Manoff\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1914|04|25|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1965|02|10|1914|04|15|mf=yes}} \n| death_place               = New York City, U.S.\n| resting_place             = \n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = American\n| other_names               = Joel Carpenter\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Screenwriter, novelist, playwright\n| years_active              = 1942&ndash;1965\n| known_for                 = \n| spouse                    =  \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = 4, including [[Dinah Manoff]]\n| parents                   = \n| relatives                 = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Arnold Manoff''' (April 25, 1914 &ndash; February 10, 1965) was an American [[screenwriter]] who was [[Hollywood blacklist|blacklisted]] by the [[Hollywood]] [[movie studio]] bosses in the 1950s.<ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_7gmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6EQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6354,1438228&dq=arnold+manoff+died&hl=en|title=Talking With Lee Grant|last=Sanello|first=Frank|date=1989-02-15|work=Walker County Messenger|page=4B|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the blacklist he wrote under a pseudonym through the 1960s. Manoff's experiences while blacklisted were among the inspirations for the 1976 film ''[[The Front]]''.\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early writing ===\nManoff was born in New York City. He did not attend college and quit school at age fifteen.<ref name=\"Telegram review\">{{cite news |title=The Submerged; TELEGRAM FROM HEAVEN. By Arnold Manoff (review) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1942/09/27/archives/the-submerged-telegram-from-heaven-by-arnold-manoff-307-pp-new-york.html?searchResultPosition=2|accessdate=21 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=27 September 1942 |language=en}}</ref> He began writing and won a contest in ''[[Story (magazine)|Story]]'' magazine. In the 1930s he assembled games and songs of the streets of the city for the [[Works Progress Administration]]'s Writer's Project.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHis first novel, ''Telegram From Heaven,'' published by [[Dial Press]] in 1942, recounts the struggle of an unemployed stenographer from the viewpoint of the stenographer, A review of the book in ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that Manoff  \"has written a readable book, pulsing with life,\" and that he \"knows the life of the submerged poor and he has an intimate sympathy for them.\"<ref name=\"Telegram review\" />\n\n=== Films and theater ===\nManoff's first screenplay was made into the 1944 film ''[[Man from Frisco]]''. Three more of his screenplays were made into movies prior to his being blacklisted: ''[[My Buddy (film)|My Buddy]]'' (1944), ''[[Casbah]]'' (1948, starring [[Peter Lorre]] and [[Yvonne De Carlo]]), and ''[[No Minor Vices]]'' (1948, starring [[Dana Andrews]], [[Lilli Palmer]], and [[Louis Jordan]].\n\nHis [[novella]] ''All You Need is One Good Break'' was published in ''Story'' and produced on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1950, in a production starring [[John Berry (film director)|John Berry]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The reviews were described by featured player [[Lee Grant]] as  \"scathing.\"<ref name=\":2\">Grant, Lee (2014). ''I Said Yes to Everything: A Memoir''. Blue Rider Press. {{ISBN|978-0147516282}}.</ref> ''The New York Times'' theater critic [[Brooks Atkinson]]  called the play \"a tabloid tale about a tenement wastrel\" and said it was \"maudlin when it was not commonplace.\"<ref name=\"times review of one good\">{{cite news |last1=Atkinson |first1=Brooks |title='ONE GOOD BREAK' ARRIVES TONIGHT; Arnold Manoff Play to Open at the Mansfield--Bromberg and Berry Head Cast TO ACHIEVE YEAR'S RUN |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/09/archives/one-good-break-arrives-tonight-arnold-manoff-play-to-open-at-the.html?searchResultPosition=8 |work=The New York Times |date=9 February 1950 |page=20}}</ref>  ''[[The Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]'' also panned the play, calling it a \"tiresome, rather whiny business.\" The review praised the performance of [[Lee Grant]]<ref name=\"Bklyn Eagle review\">{{cite news |last1=Sheaffer |first1=Lous |title=Curtain Time: |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39404154/brookyn_eagle_review_of_one_good_break/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle |date=10 February 1950 |pages=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>, who left the hit play ''[[Detective Story (play)|Detective Story]]'' to join the cast. ''All You Need is One Good Break'' closed after four performances<ref>{{cite news |title=Broadway Play A Quick Failure |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39415166/broadway_play_a_quick_failure/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Tampa Tribune |agency=United Press |date=24 March 1950 |pages=40}}</ref> but was briefly revived later that year.\n\n=== Blacklisting ===\nIn April 1951, director [[Edward Dmytryk]] testified before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) that Manoff and other film writers and directors were members of the [[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Tribune - Dmytryk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39402157/director_tells_of_communism_in_hollywood/|title=Director Tells of Communism in Hollywood|last=Edwards|first=Willard|date=26 April 1951|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=21 November 2019|pages=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Later that year he was again identified before HUAC as a Communist by screenwriter and admitted former Communist Leo Townsend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Korman |first1=Seymour |title=Commies Trying to Infiltrate Films, Quiz Told |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39402368/commies_trying_to_infiltrate_films/ |accessdate=21 November 2019 |work=Chicago Tribune |date=19 September 1951 |pages=8|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He was blacklisted.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nGrant, who became his wife, was also blacklisted after she gave an impassioned eulogy at the memorial service for the blacklisted actor [[J. Edward Bromberg]], who appeared in ''All You Need is One Good Break''. Her name later appeared in the publication ''[[Red Channels]]'', and as a result, for the next ten years,<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.cbsnews.com/news/lee-grant-on-life-beyond-the-hollywood-blacklist \"Lee Grant on life beyond the Hollywood blacklist\"], CBSnews.com, August 3, 2014.</ref> she too was blacklisted and her work in television and movies was limited.<ref name=\"TCM\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7YLf3Ga4ZBM Turner Classic Movies \"Evening With Lee Grant\" (1of4), ''Detective Story''], interview with [[Robert Osborne]], 2014</ref> In a 2014 interview, Grant said that she knew nothing about Communism and said \"it was one of the big rifts between my husband and myself. He was a Communist. And I didn't have the base for that kind of philosophy. I just couldn't understand it.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Later career ===\nWhile they were blacklisted, Manoff and fellow writers [[Abraham Polonsky]] and [[Walter Bernstein]] formed what has been described as a \"kind of collective to help each other survive by writing under the table\" for television, mainly for the historical series''[[You Are There (series)|You Are There.]]''<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hideinplainsight00buhl|title=Hide in plain sight : the Hollywood blacklistees in film and television, 1950-2002|last=Buhle|first=Paul|date=2003|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|others=Wagner, Dave.|year=|isbn=1-4039-6144-1|location=New York|pages=|oclc=51586908|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nManoff used the pseudonym \"Joel Carpenter.\"  In addition to ''You Are There'', he wrote episodes of ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', and ''[[The Defenders (1961 TV series)|The Defenders]]''. At the time of his death in 1965 he was adapting for film a [[Bernard Malamud]] story that was to star [[Harry Belafonte]].<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Walter Grauman]], who directed a Naked City episode written by Manoff, said years later that he was shocked to learn that his real name was not \"Carpenter\" and discovered it by accident. He called Manoff a \"terrific writer.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/people/arnold-manoff?clip=97399|title=Walter E. Grauman Interview Part 1 of 3|last=|first=|date=2017-10-23|website=Television Academy Interviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nWalter Bernstein described Manoff was \"a talent that never really flourished.\" A number of blacklisted writers produced scripts for the ''You Are There'' series'','' and author Erik Christiansen writes that \"Arnold Manoff's story is the saddest of the ''You Are There'' team\" and that he had difficulty getting off the blacklist.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/827842007|title=Channeling the past : politicizing history in postwar America|last=Christiansen|first=Erik|date=2013|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=|isbn=0-299-28903-6|location=Madison|pages=|oclc=827842007}}</ref>\n\nThe informal collective of Manoff, Bernstein and Polonsky was dramatized in the 1976 film ''[[The Front]],'' which was written by Bernstein. In an early scene, the [[Michael Murphy (actor)|Michael Murphy]] character, modeled on Bernstein, introduces the [[Woody Allen]] character to two other blacklisted writers''.''<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn her 2014 memoir ''I Said Yes to Everything'', Lee Grant wrote that Manoff was known as \"the silver fox\" when she first met him in 1950 during rehearsals for ''All You Need is One Good Break'', because of his white hair that made him look older than his 36 years. He'd already been married three times and had a nine-year-old daughter with his second wife, Ruth. He was married at the time to Marjorie MacGregor, the mother of his two sons, Tom and Michael. Grant recounted that she and Manoff were \"an item\" during production of the play.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/12646/marjorie-mcgregor-archives|title=The Marjorie Jean MacGregor Archive|publisher=tommanoff.com|accessdate=14 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615130113/http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/12646/marjorie-mcgregor-archives|archivedate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/9216/michael-manoff|title=Michael Manoff 1946 \u2013 2012|publisher=tommanoff.com|accessdate=14 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113065323/http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/9216/michael-manoff|archivedate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nGrant wrote that she was living at home before their marriage, and that her parents did not approve. She said that there was a \"[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]\" aspect to their marriage, and that Manoff sought to instruct her on Soviet literature and politics. She wrote that Manoff had little interest in her upbringing and that she never met most members of his family, including his mother.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nManoff and Grant had a daughter, [[Dinah Manoff]], who became an actress. They were separated at the time of his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/people/arnold-manoff?clip=37502|title=Lee Grant Interview Part 5 of 7|last=|first=|date=2017-10-23|website=Television Academy Interviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nManoff died in 1965 of a heart ailment. He was survived by two daughters, two sons, two sisters and his mother.<ref name=\"walker\" /><ref name=\"people\">{{cite journal|last=Rein|first=Richard K.|date=1982-04-26|title=She's Lee Grant's Daughter, but Dinah Manoff Figures She Ought to Be in Pictures Too|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20082008,00.html|journal=People|volume=17|issue=16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/12/archives/arnold-manoff-filmwriter-50-author-also-of-plays-for-tv-dies.html |title=Arnold Manoff, Filmwriter, 50; Author Also of Plays for TV Dies -- Blacklisted in 50's |author=Staff writers |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1965-02-12 |access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|543529|Arnold Manoff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manoff, Arnold}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American screenwriter and political activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Arnold Manoff\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1914|04|25|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1965|02|10|1914|04|15|mf=yes}} \n| death_place               = New York City, U.S.\n| resting_place             = \n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = American\n| other_names               = Joel Carpenter\n| ethnicity                 = \n| citizenship               = \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Screenwriter, novelist, playwright\n| years_active              = 1942&ndash;1965\n| known_for                 = \n| spouse                    =  \n| partner                   = \n| children                  = 4, including [[Dinah Manoff]]\n| parents                   = \n| relatives                 = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Arnold Manoff''' (April 25, 1914 &ndash; February 10, 1965) was an American [[screenwriter]] who was [[Hollywood blacklist|blacklisted]] by the [[Hollywood]] [[movie studio]] bosses in the 1950s.<ref name=\"walker\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_7gmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6EQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6354,1438228&dq=arnold+manoff+died&hl=en|title=Talking With Lee Grant|last=Sanello|first=Frank|date=1989-02-15|work=Walker County Messenger|page=4B|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the blacklist he wrote under a pseudonym through the 1960s. Manoff's experiences while blacklisted were among the inspirations for the 1976 film ''[[The Front]]''.\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early writing ===\nManoff was born in New York City. He did not attend college and quit school at age fifteen.<ref name=\"Telegram review\">{{cite news |title=The Submerged; TELEGRAM FROM HEAVEN. By Arnold Manoff (review) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1942/09/27/archives/the-submerged-telegram-from-heaven-by-arnold-manoff-307-pp-new-york.html?searchResultPosition=2|accessdate=21 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=27 September 1942 |language=en}}</ref> He began writing and won a contest in ''[[Story (magazine)|Story]]'' magazine. In the 1930s he assembled games and songs of the streets of the city for the [[Works Progress Administration]]'s Writer's Project.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHis first novel, ''Telegram From Heaven,'' published by [[Dial Press]] in 1942, recounts the struggle of an unemployed stenographer from the viewpoint of the stenographer, A ''[[New York Times]]'' review of the book said that Manoff  \"has written a readable book, pulsing with life,\" and that he \"knows the life of the submerged poor and he has an intimate sympathy for them.\"<ref name=\"Telegram review\" /> \n\n=== Films and theater ===\nManoff's first screenplay was made into the 1944 film ''[[Man from Frisco]]''. Three more of his screenplays were made into movies prior to his being blacklisted: ''[[My Buddy (film)|My Buddy]]'' (1944), ''[[Casbah]]'' (1948, starring [[Peter Lorre]] and [[Yvonne De Carlo]]), and ''[[No Minor Vices]]'' (1948, starring [[Dana Andrews]], [[Lilli Palmer]], and [[Louis Jordan]].\n\nHis [[novella]] ''All You Need is One Good Break'' was published in ''Story'' and produced on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1950, in a production starring [[John Berry (film director)|John Berry]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The reviews were described by featured player [[Lee Grant]] as  \"scathing.\"<ref name=\":2\">Grant, Lee (2014). ''I Said Yes to Everything: A Memoir''. Blue Rider Press. {{ISBN|978-0147516282}}.</ref> ''New York Times'' theater critic [[Brooks Atkinson]]  called the play \"a tabloid tale about a tenement wastrel\" and said it was \"maudlin when it was not commonplace.\"<ref name=\"times review of one good\">{{cite news |last1=Atkinson |first1=Brooks |title='ONE GOOD BREAK' ARRIVES TONIGHT; Arnold Manoff Play to Open at the Mansfield--Bromberg and Berry Head Cast TO ACHIEVE YEAR'S RUN |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/02/09/archives/one-good-break-arrives-tonight-arnold-manoff-play-to-open-at-the.html?searchResultPosition=8 |work=The New York Times |date=9 February 1950 |page=20}}</ref>  ''[[The Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]'' also panned the play, calling it a \"tiresome, rather whiny business.\" The review praised the performance of [[Lee Grant]]<ref name=\"Bklyn Eagle review\">{{cite news |last1=Sheaffer |first1=Lous |title=Curtain Time: |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39404154/brookyn_eagle_review_of_one_good_break/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle |date=10 February 1950 |pages=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>, who left the hit play ''[[Detective Story (play)|Detective Story]]'' to join the cast. ''All You Need is One Good Break'' closed after four performances<ref>{{cite news |title=Broadway Play A Quick Failure |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39415166/broadway_play_a_quick_failure/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=The Tampa Tribune |agency=United Press |date=24 March 1950 |pages=40}}</ref> but was briefly revived later that year.\n\n=== Blacklisting ===\nIn April 1951, director [[Edward Dmytryk]] testified before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) that Manoff and other film writers and directors were members of the [[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Tribune - Dmytryk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39402157/director_tells_of_communism_in_hollywood/|title=Director Tells of Communism in Hollywood|last=Edwards|first=Willard|date=26 April 1951|work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=21 November 2019|pages=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Later that year he was again identified before HUAC as a Communist by screenwriter and admitted former Communist Leo Townsend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Korman |first1=Seymour |title=Commies Trying to Infiltrate Films, Quiz Told |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39402368/commies_trying_to_infiltrate_films/ |accessdate=21 November 2019 |work=Chicago Tribune |date=19 September 1951 |pages=8|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He was blacklisted.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nGrant, who became his wife, was also blacklisted after she gave an impassioned eulogy at the memorial service for the blacklisted actor [[J. Edward Bromberg]], who appeared in ''All You Need is One Good Break''. Her name later appeared in the publication ''[[Red Channels]]'', and as a result, for the next ten years,<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.cbsnews.com/news/lee-grant-on-life-beyond-the-hollywood-blacklist \"Lee Grant on life beyond the Hollywood blacklist\"], CBSnews.com, August 3, 2014.</ref> she too was blacklisted and her work in television and movies was limited.<ref name=\"TCM\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7YLf3Ga4ZBM Turner Classic Movies \"Evening With Lee Grant\" (1of4), ''Detective Story''], interview with [[Robert Osborne]], 2014</ref> In a 2014 interview, Grant said that she knew nothing about Communism and said \"it was one of the big rifts between my husband and myself. He was a Communist. And I didn't have the base for that kind of philosophy. I just couldn't understand it.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Later career ===\nWhile they were blacklisted, Manoff and fellow writers [[Abraham Polonsky]] and [[Walter Bernstein]] formed what has been described as a \"kind of collective to help each other survive by writing under the table\" for television, mainly for the historical series''[[You Are There (series)|You Are There.]]''<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hideinplainsight00buhl|title=Hide in plain sight : the Hollywood blacklistees in film and television, 1950-2002|last=Buhle|first=Paul|date=2003|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|others=Wagner, Dave.|year=|isbn=1-4039-6144-1|location=New York|pages=|oclc=51586908|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nManoff used the pseudonym \"Joel Carpenter.\"  In addition to ''You Are There'', he wrote episodes of ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', and ''[[The Defenders (1961 TV series)|The Defenders]]''. At the time of his death in 1965 he was adapting for film a [[Bernard Malamud]] story that was to star [[Harry Belafonte]].<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Walter Grauman]], who directed a Naked City episode written by Manoff, said years later that he was shocked to learn that his real name was not \"Carpenter\" and discovered it by accident. He called Manoff a \"terrific writer.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/people/arnold-manoff?clip=97399|title=Walter E. Grauman Interview Part 1 of 3|last=|first=|date=2017-10-23|website=Television Academy Interviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nWalter Bernstein described Manoff was \"a talent that never really flourished.\" A number of blacklisted writers produced scripts for the ''You Are There'' series'','' and author Erik Christiansen writes that \"Arnold Manoff's story is the saddest of the ''You Are There'' team\" and that he had difficulty getting off the blacklist.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/827842007|title=Channeling the past : politicizing history in postwar America|last=Christiansen|first=Erik|date=2013|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=|isbn=0-299-28903-6|location=Madison|pages=|oclc=827842007}}</ref>\n\nThe informal collective of Manoff, Bernstein and Polonsky was dramatized in the 1976 film ''[[The Front]],'' which was written by Bernstein. In an early scene, the [[Michael Murphy (actor)|Michael Murphy]] character, modeled on Bernstein, introduces the [[Woody Allen]] character to two other blacklisted writers''.''<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\n==Personal life==\nIn her 2014 memoir ''I Said Yes to Everything'', Lee Grant wrote that Manoff was known as \"the silver fox\" when she first met him in 1950 during rehearsals for ''All You Need is One Good Break'', because of his white hair that made him look older than his 36 years. He'd already been married three times and had a nine-year-old daughter with his second wife, Ruth. He was married at the time to Marjorie MacGregor, the mother of his two sons, Tom and Michael. Grant recounted that she and Manoff were \"an item\" during production of the play.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/12646/marjorie-mcgregor-archives|title=The Marjorie Jean MacGregor Archive|publisher=tommanoff.com|accessdate=14 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615130113/http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/12646/marjorie-mcgregor-archives|archivedate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/9216/michael-manoff|title=Michael Manoff 1946 \u2013 2012|publisher=tommanoff.com|accessdate=14 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113065323/http://www.tommanoff.com/articles/9216/michael-manoff|archivedate=13 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nGrant wrote that she was living at home before their marriage, and that her parents did not approve. She said that there was a \"[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]\" aspect to their marriage, and that Manoff sought to instruct her on Soviet literature and politics. She wrote that Manoff had little interest in her upbringing and that she never met most members of his family, including his mother.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nManoff and Grant had a daughter, [[Dinah Manoff]], who became an actress. They were separated at the time of his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interviews.televisionacademy.com/people/arnold-manoff?clip=37502|title=Lee Grant Interview Part 5 of 7|last=|first=|date=2017-10-23|website=Television Academy Interviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nManoff died in 1965 of a heart ailment. He was survived by two daughters, two sons, two sisters and his mother.<ref name=\"walker\" /><ref name=\"people\">{{cite journal|last=Rein|first=Richard K.|date=1982-04-26|title=She's Lee Grant's Daughter, but Dinah Manoff Figures She Ought to Be in Pictures Too|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20082008,00.html|journal=People|volume=17|issue=16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/12/archives/arnold-manoff-filmwriter-50-author-also-of-plays-for-tv-dies.html |title=Arnold Manoff, Filmwriter, 50; Author Also of Plays for TV Dies -- Blacklisted in 50's |author=Staff writers |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1965-02-12 |access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|543529|Arnold Manoff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manoff, Arnold}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{US-screen-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "the work's name is \"The New York Times\", removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arnold_Manoff"}
